docs.abstract: Voters are justifiably upset, but they’ll probably support the wrong people.
docs.snippet: Voters are justifiably upset, but they’ll probably support the wrong people.
docs.lead_paragraph: Results from Tuesday’s primaries in California suggest that crime may be a big issue in the midterm elections. In San Francisco, a progressive prosecutor was ousted in a recall vote. In Los Angeles, a businessman and former Republican who has run for mayor on the promise to be a big crime fighter made a strong showing.

docs.abstract: Stephanie Insalaco, a bereavement therapist, and Thomas Ciccotta, a lawyer who works with sexual abuse survivors, fell more in love by witnessing the empathy each has shown others.
docs.snippet: Stephanie Insalaco, a bereavement therapist, and Thomas Ciccotta, a lawyer who works with sexual abuse survivors, fell more in love by witnessing the empathy each has shown others.
docs.lead_paragraph: Of all the traits that have attracted Stephanie Nicole Insalaco and Thomas John Ciccotta to one another over the course of their relationship, perhaps none has drawn them closer than how each has treated other people along the way.

docs.abstract: Some urban police departments are struggling to keep their numbers up.
docs.snippet: Some urban police departments are struggling to keep their numbers up.
docs.lead_paragraph: For the second time in three years, the United States enters the summer amid a storm of anger at the police. The reports and videos suggesting a delayed and chaotic police response to the Uvalde shooting and the conflicting statements made by law enforcement leadership have rightfully bewildered and enraged millions of people across the country.

headline.main: Violent Crime Is Up as Cities Lose Police Officers. What Now?
headline.print_headline: Is the Thin Blue Line Getting Thinner?

docs.abstract: As it turns 200, the Mauritshuis, home of “Girl With a Pearl Earring,” is welcoming discussion about its building’s ties to the history of slavery.

docs.lead_paragraph: The Mauritshuis in The Hague is one of the world’s much-loved museums, a jewel case for such artistic gems as Vermeer’s “Girl With a Pearl Earring” and Rembrandt’s “Anatomy Lesson of Dr. Nicolaes Tulp.”

headline.main: A Dutch Museum Celebrates, and Reflects

docs.abstract: The technology giant will stop offering automated tools that predict a person’s gender, age and emotional state and will restrict the use of its facial recognition tool.
docs.snippet: The technology giant will stop offering automated tools that predict a person’s gender, age and emotional state and will restrict the use of its facial recognition tool.
docs.lead_paragraph: For years, activists and academics have been raising concerns that facial analysis software that claims to be able to identify a person’s age, gender and emotional state can be biased, unreliable or invasive — and shouldn’t be sold.

headline.main: Microsoft Plans to Eliminate Face Analysis Tools in Push for ‘Responsible A.I.’
headline.print_headline: Microsoft to Delete Facial Analysis Tools From A.I.

docs.abstract: This year’s summit for the group of nations came as they grappled with the place of the monarchy, and as many were forging connections with powers like China and Russia.
docs.snippet: This year’s summit for the group of nations came as they grappled with the place of the monarchy, and as many were forging connections with powers like China and Russia.
docs.lead_paragraph: KIGALI, Rwanda — As the leaders of the Commonwealth wrapped up a week of closed-door meetings, panel discussions and formal dinners on Saturday in Rwanda, this “family of nations” still stood at a crossroads, with questions remaining about its usefulness and whether it can reinvent itself for the 21st century.

headline.main: Commonwealth’s Fissures Exposed at Week of Meetings
headline.print_headline: Commonwealth Summit Bares Internal Conflicts in ‘Family of Nations’

docs.abstract: The ceramic artist Theaster Gates says his “Black Chapel” in London’s Kensington Gardens is about optimism and openness, even as it pays tribute to his late father.
docs.snippet: The ceramic artist Theaster Gates says his “Black Chapel” in London’s Kensington Gardens is about optimism and openness, even as it pays tribute to his late father.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — The wooden edifice looms quietly over the trees and lawns of Kensington Gardens. Shaped like a bulky cylinder and painted black, it has apertures on two sides and a circular opening in the ceiling that lets light into what is otherwise a dark and contemplative space.

headline.main: A Chicago Roofer’s Legacy Finds a Home in the Serpentine Pavilion

docs.abstract: Where is the women’s movement when we need it most?
docs.snippet: Where is the women’s movement when we need it most?
docs.lead_paragraph: The Drift, a buzzy literary journal founded by Kiara Barrow and Rebecca Panovka, left-leaning women in their late 20s, published a series of short essays earlier this year under the rubric, “What to Do About Feminism.” “For a long time now, we’ve had the sense that feminism is in trouble,” Barrow and Panovka wrote in the introduction. They described an ambient feeling that feminism has been sapped of cultural vitality, even as an anti-feminist backlash is gathering momentum, and that young people especially were turning against the movement.
